    "narrative": "The Austin Waves enter today\u2019s slate with **Gunnar Henderson** as the clear offensive engine. With a score of 83.29, he represents our strongest play, bolstered by a 16% park factor enhancement and an aggressive 10% jump from his lead-off spot. While a 34% rain risk requires monitoring, his matchup against Brayan Bello is favorable enough to prioritize him despite the weather volatility. **Kyle Tucker** follows closely with a 73.60 rating; his stability against Jameson Taillon makes him a core foundation piece for production across all categories. We are also looking for a breakout performance from **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.** (69.24), whose strong xwOBA of 0.384 and favorable park conditions offset the slight drag created by the platoon matchup against Gavin Williams.\n\nStrategic decisions for the remainder of the lineup hinged on optimizing for the scarcity of stolen bases and specific pitching matchups. **Nasim Nunez** (62.48) earns a spot over alternatives because his profile offers more utility against Bryan Hudson than some of our higher-floor bench options. **Heliot Ramos** (59.77) was locked in primarily due to the rare efficiency gain\u2014a 97th-percentile stolen base opportunity against Sandy Alcantara\u2019s slower delivery, which provides a much-needed boost in our scarcest category. **Drake Baldwin** (64.49) remains an elite start, taking advantage of Andrew Painter\u2019s xERA of 4.42, while **Andy Pages** (61.67) and **Liam Hicks** (58.41) round out the rotation as beneficiaries of favorable park and platoon alignments.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision was bypassing **Nolan Schanuel** (56.02). He pushed the bottom of our lineup for the final spot, but the optimizer ultimately deferred to the higher upside of **Heliot Ramos** and **Josh Jung** given the situational advantages presented by their respective opponents. **Coby Mayo** (54.82) also lingered in consideration, but the combined negative impact of an assumed ninth-spot order and the looming 34% rain risk ultimately made him a liability compared to the current starters. We continue to monitor the status of **Jackson Merrill**, **Jordan Westburg**, **Jacob Wilson**, **Jorge Polanco**, **Josh Lowe**, **Marcell Ozuna**, and **Brady House**, who remain on the bench as we strictly adhere to our daily efficiency thresholds to preserve our limited game caps for more optimal leverage points later in the week.",
